		<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Growing up in Scotland, Stephen McLaren was drawn to a land on the other side of the Atlantic, a garden paradise he discovered years later had landscapes that reminded him of home. âSince I was a teenager, Iâve always wanted to visit Jamaica and savor its Caribbean heat, its energy, its natural beauty,â Mr. McLaren said. âI craved to experience it firsthand both as a photographer and a visitor.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While the sun-soaked island may seem to be the polar opposite of Scotland, he would learn that it had a shared â and disturbing â heritage with his homeland, dating to an era when Scottish plantation owners built their fortunes on slave labor. Mr. McLaren discovered this troubling connection after reading âTo the Ends of the Earth,â by the Scottish scholar Tom Devine, an engaging history of the Scottish diaspora. According to the book, the huge profits that flowed from Jamaica supercharged Scottish industries like fishing, weaving, railways and mining. Mr. McLaren also learned that huge country estates, mansions and schools were built all over Scotland with the wealth that enslaved Africans generated for nearly 150 years under the Caribbean sun.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When Anne Lyden, photography director of the Scottish National Portrait Gallery, asked Document Scotland, a collective that includes Mr. McLaren, to produce a series of works in response to the aftermath of the Scottish independence referendum, he decided to explore that history. Produced over two months, â<a href="//www.stephenmclaren.co.uk/jamaica-a-sweet-forgetting">A Sweet Forgetting</a>â revives a forgotten aspect of his countryâs past.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Although Mr. McLarenâs university studies included economic history, Scotlandâs slave trade connections were not taught. He said the Scottish role in the eventual emancipation of the enslaved was always the more resonant tale. Interested in exploring the genealogical legacy of the period, Mr. McLaren traveled to Jamaica and then to Scotland to photograph the estates amassed by rich Scottish sugar plantation owners and how the vast profits from the slave economy in Jamaica left their mark.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-2/20151006-lens-stephen-2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-2/20151006-lens-stephen-2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-2/20151006-lens-stephen-2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003961554" width="480" height="360" alt="A street corner lottery store in a village in western Jamaica. The town, Culloden, was named after a 1746 Scottish battlefield." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-2/20151006-lens-stephen-2-superJumbo.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="A street corner lottery store in a village in western Jamaica. The town, Culloden, was named after a 1746 Scottish battlefield." data-mediaviewer-credit="Stephen McLaren" /><meta itemprop="height" content="360"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A street corner lottery store in a village in western Jamaica. The town, Culloden, was named after a 1746 Scottish battlefield.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stephen McLaren</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To do this project, he had to take a different approach than what he was used to in street photography. Rather than be impulsive and shoot as much as he could, Mr. McLaren prepared carefully and learned the historical context. He read books like James Robertsonâs âJoseph Knight,â a true story about a rich Scottish plantation owner, John Wedderburn, and the enslaved African who sued and won his freedom. He also read the Jamaican authors Marlon James and Diana Macaulay and material by the historians Eric Graham, Sir Geoff Palmer and Stephen Mullen and researched issues surrounding the <a href="//www.bbc.com/news/uk-34401412">case for reparations</a> against Britain.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYou canât shoot a project like this with a street photographerâs mind-set,â Mr. McLaren said. âRegardless of the amount of research put into a project, Iâm always looking for something in a scene that I donât know about.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Visiting locales and towns with Scottish names like Glen Isla and meeting Jamaicans with Scottish surnames that could be traced to the days of sugar plantations was an interesting discovery for him. Yet some residents in Jamaica of Inverness, Roxborough and Culloden were generally unaware that their towns were named after places in Scotland, despite knowing about slavery on the island.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe people I met had an interest in their backgrounds, but often they hadnât gotten to the bottom of it,â said Mr. McLaren, who is based in San Francisco. âThe same is true for myself. I know vaguely where I come from in geographic terms. Thereâs no neat narrative for peopleâs past lives.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-1/20151006-lens-stephen-1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-1/20151006-lens-stephen-1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-1/20151006-lens-stephen-1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003961551" width="480" height="360" alt="The Caymanas sugar plantation." class="media-viewer-candidate" data-mediaviewer-src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/06/blogs/20151006-lens-stephen-1/20151006-lens-stephen-1-superJumbo.jpg" data-mediaviewer-caption="The Caymanas sugar plantation." data-mediaviewer-credit="Stephen McLaren" /><meta itemprop="height" content="360"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The Caymanas sugar plantation.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stephen McLaren</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Scotland, he gradually saw things anew â for example, on the grounds of Blackness Castle, where he photographed trees with ropes hanging from branches. His first thought was of his childhood, when he played on swings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThen it hit me like a delayed punch to the gut that it might convey something else to another person,â he said. âYou wonder if a photo like that will resonate with audiences and in what way. Iâm conscious that there are issues and traumas there that could be talked around and possibly forgotten again. Thatâs why Iâm doing this and it comes back to the original concept. I want to bring these things back to the surface to use what photography can do in terms of allusion and metaphor.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Today, Jamaicaâs economy relies mostly on agriculture and tourism, but sugar remains the oldest continuously operating industry. With a bit of envy, Mr. McLaren said that while Jamaica enjoyed independence, Scottish voters rejected that option last year in a referendum. In spite of its poverty and colonial history, Jamaica is self-confident and its people maintain a self-assured way of life, in charge of their own destiny.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Confronting Scotlandâs history and its connection to Jamaica isnât something that can be done in one visual project, Mr. McLaren acknowledged, but he said he hoped that his work facilitated more conversation and that the Scottish reckon somehow with their past.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âForgetting is a soothing kind of feeling,â he said. âIn this subject matter there would have been a period when slave owners themselves and the general Scottish population would like to pretend no one had any culpability in how slavery impacted the lives and futures of others.â</p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>âA Sweet Forgettingâ is on display at Document Scotlandâs âThe Ties That Bindâ exhibition at the Scottish National Portrait Gallery through April 26, 2016.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Fayemi Shakur is a writer based in Newark. Her work has been featured online and in print in Nueva Luz Photographic Journal, The International Review of African American Art, and Hycide Magazine.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Follow @<a href="https://www.twitter.com/7fayemi">7fayemi</a> and @<a href="https://www.twitter.com/#!/nytimesphoto">nytimesphoto</a> on Twitter. You can also find us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/nytimesphoto?ref=hl">Facebook</a> and <a href="https://instagram.com/nytimes/">Instagram</a>. </em></p>
        <div class="story theme-main">
                </div>
        	</div>
	</article>
				</div><!-- end content -->
